Slide 15:
Language of a Method
Suppose M(w) returns false, we can replace M(w) by false
as shown below:
boolean N1(String x)
{
boolean p = false;
// Used to be boolean p = M(w);
if(p)
return true;
else
return false;
}
Now, what is the language of the above method N1?
The language of the method N1() is ∅
This is under the assumption that M(w) returns false
So, here is what we can say about the method N1() so far:
If M(w) returns true, the language of N1() is Σ∗
If M(w) returns false, the language of N1() is ∅
Thumrongsak Kosiyatrakul tkosiyat@cs.pitt.edu
